The issue with the current implementation is that it is only searching for the presence of the keywords "TABLE" and "COLUMNS" in the text. However, it is not considering the structure of the text to determine if it represents a table or columns.

To address this issue, we can modify the function to analyze the structure of the text to determine if it represents a table or columns. We can look for patterns such as rows of data with consistent column separators or headers for each column to identify a table or columns.

Let's update the function to implement this improved logic:

```javascript
function doesItContainTableOrColumns(text) {
  // Split the text into lines
  const lines = text.split('\n').map(line => line.trim());

  // Check if the text represents a table
  if (lines.length >= 3) {
    const headerRow = lines[1].split(/\s{2,}/); // Split the second line by multiple spaces
    const dataRow = lines[2].split(/\s{2,}/); // Split the third line by multiple spaces
    if (headerRow.length === dataRow.length) {
      return "TABLE";
    }
  }

  // Check if the text represents columns
  const columnHeaders = lines[0].split(/\s{2,}/); // Split the first line by multiple spaces
  if (columnHeaders.length > 1) {
    return "COLUMNS";
  }

  // If the text does not match the table or column structure, return "NORMAL"
  return "NORMAL";
}
```

By analyzing the structure of the text data, we can determine whether it represents a table, columns, both, or neither based on the presence of consistent column separators and headers.

The issue with the current implementation is that it's assuming a specific structure of a table that may not always be present in the input text. The function is checking for a consistent number of columns in the second and third lines, and if they match, it identifies it as a "TABLE". This assumption may not hold true for all types of table structures.

To improve the function, we need to implement a more robust analysis of the text structure to accurately identify whether it represents a table, columns, both, or neither. We also need to consider the nested structure of the text instead of only looking at the initial lines.

Let's update the function to consider the entire text and look for consistent column structures and header patterns to determine if it's a table or columns:

```javascript
function doesItContainTableOrColumns(text) {
  const lines = text.split('\n').map(line => line.trim());

  // Check if the text represents a table
  let isTable = true;
  let prevRowColumns = 0;
  for (let i = 1; i < lines.length; i++) {
    const rowColumns = lines[i].split(/\s{2,}/).length;
    if (i === 1) {
      prevRowColumns = rowColumns;
    } else {
      if (rowColumns !== prevRowColumns) {
        isTable = false;
        break;
      }
    }
  }
  if (isTable) {
    return "TABLE";
  }

  // Check if the text represents columns
  const columnHeaders = lines[0].split(/\s{2,}/);
  if (columnHeaders.length > 1) {
    return "COLUMNS";
  }

  // If the text does not match the table or column structure, return "NORMAL"
  return "NORMAL";
}
```

In this updated function, we iterate through each row of the text to check for a consistent number of columns. If the number of columns is consistent throughout the entire text, we identify it as a "TABLE". If the first line contains multiple columns, we identify it as "COLUMNS", and if neither of these conditions is met, we identify it as "NORMAL".

This approach provides a more comprehensive analysis of the text structure to accurately classify it as table, columns, both, or neither.
